##Apple, Huawei and Samsung hit by an epidemic?

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

China makes 70% of the world's smartphones

The restrictions on segregation caused delays in starting factories and a shortage of labour

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"while some mobile phone production has moved to countries such as Vietnam and India, the supply system has been in China. The supply system is more valuable than the assembly line, so we should cherish the hard-won supply chain, restore it as soon as possible and maintain its advantages,"Wang Jianzhou, former chairman of China Mobile, told China News Weekly.

The new crown pneumonia outbreak has made the already difficult mobile phone market even more difficult.

In recent years, the smartphone market continues to decline, technology products to extend the life cycle of consumer exchange, smartphone innovation is slowing down, the market competition is increasingly brutal. Under the epidemic, users stay indoors, stores close, logistics stop, supply chain manufacturers delay to resume work, thorny problems one after another.

The mobile industry event, MWC 2020, scheduled for Feb. 24, was canceled, disrupting the normal production and sales rhythm of mobile phone manufacturers and reducing mobile phone shipments. Only February 24, Huawei, glory, realme are held in different regions of the online global launch, new products all debut.

Mobile phone sales are also transferred to the front line, the mobile phone manufacturers to launch online booking, offline home delivery, the whole process of disinfection, no contact distribution. While apple, Huawei, Xiaomi and other headquarter manufacturers are also looking for revenue sources beyond mobile phones, expanding overseas, software services become the main focus.

Slow resumption of work and weak demand

IDC, a market research firm, believes that in the first two weeks of January 2020, while the overall market performance improved year-on-year, the Spring Festival holiday, which was supposed to be the peak season for sales, was affected by the epidemic and met with a "lull" . The domestic mobile phone market will face a sharp decline of about 40 per cent year-on-year from January to February, and even if the outbreak is brought under control in March, it will struggle to return to the level of the same period last year. The domestic mobile phone market will decline by at least 30% in the first quarter, and is expected to rebound in the second and second half of the year, with total shipments expected to decline by 4% for the full year, as demand begins to release once the rhythm of the product returns to normal.

In January 2020, the domestic mobile phone market shipped 20.813 million units, down 38.9 percent year-on-year, of which 5.465 million units, or 26.26 percent of the total, according to a report released by the China Academy of Information and Communications Research on Feb. 24. Domestic-brand mobile phone shipments totaled 18.319 million units, down 42.9 percent year-on-year and accounting for 88.0 percent of mobile phone shipments in the same period.

IDC believes that the impact of the epidemic delayed the resumption of factory hours, mobile phone manufacturers will face the ability to adjust the supply chain will be tested. Small and medium-sized players in the mobile phone industry, especially retail channel partners, will face shocks or even reshuffle during the outbreak, which will have an uncertain impact on the medium-to-long-term performance of the domestic mobile phone market.

Both ends of the supply and demand chain of mobile phone industry are impacted. Yang Xin, a researcher at the China Merchants Bank Research Institute, believes that on the demand side, mobile phones have certain optional consumption properties. With offline sales still dominating, the panic caused by the epidemic and the frequency of going out are reduced, restrain the demand of some consumers to change the machine. The economic downturn caused by the outbreak will lead to lower incomes and even job losses for some consumers, which in turn will affect the consumption of mobile phones. Domestic smartphone shipments are expected to fall by 5% in 2020 compared with the same period last year.

On the supply side, local mobile phone assembly capacity in Hubei is relatively small, but the provinces surrounding Hubei, such as Henan, Jiangxi and Hunan, have the main production bases of mobile phone industry chain companies such as Foxconn, oplite and Lens, guangdong, Zhejiang and other major mobile phone industry chain base. At the same time, the mobile phone industry chain company automation is generally not high, the number of workers, the epidemic caused many enterprises to resume work affected, may have a significant impact on the global mobile phone industry chain. In addition, the transportation capacity of many parts of the country has been greatly affected, the transportation time of some raw materials has been prolonged, and the supply of raw materials has become a disturbing factor.

Revenue falls short of expectation, each manufacturer returns to work hard

In fact, the impact on the iphone from mainland manufacturers is even more intense.

On Jan. 28, apple said it expected first quarter revenue of $63 billion to $67 billion. Now, while all 42 stores in mainland China that apple previously closed are starting to reopen, the company said in a Feb. 17 announcement that, first-quarter revenue is expected to be lower than expected due to weak demand in China, a temporary shortage of global-based supply chains, slow factory restarts and sluggish sales. Apple's shares plunged after the announcement.

China is apple's largest manufacturing base, with more than 99 percent of its iphones manufactured and assembled in the country. North America, Europe and China are apple's three biggest markets, accounting for 45% , 25% and 15% of revenue, according to the company's latest results. Foxconn is the world's largest contract electronics manufacturer, and apple relies on it for products such as mobile phones. Foxconn's inability to return to work on a large scale is bound to hurt iphone production.

In order to encourage employees to speed up the return to work, Foxconn employees incentive bonus increased again. New Hires will receive a 7,110-yuan bonus by March 31 for IDPBG and IDSBG, which are responsible for apple's mobile phone and tablet business, according to the Shenzhen campus interviewer. The previous 15,000 places have been filled, 24 places released 50010 minutes to fill. It is understood that the Shenzhen campus and the Zhengzhou campus are foxconn's two largest factories in the mainland, with a total staff of more than 400,000 people.

Sales of Apple's iphones fell 28 percent in January from the previous month, according to a UBS study. Timothy Arcuri, an analyst at UBS, said the supply and demand problems caused by the outbreak could have made February's sales figures even worse, and that Apple's recovery in the June quarter was more dependent on the demand side, making it difficult to predict.

Samsung, the world's largest mobile phone maker, has also been hit by the outbreak. In October 2019, Samsung shut down China's last mobile phone factory in Huizhou, in Guangdong Province, and moved to overseas production lines. Samsung's Galaxy Z Flip factory in South Korea has been temporarily closed after an employee was diagnosed with a new coronavirus infection. The factory in Kamei, South Korea, makes Samsung's folding screen phones, including the Samsung Galaxy Z Flip and the Galaxy Fold.

Earlier, Vietnam's Ministry of Industry and Trade said the country's manufacturing sector was facing supply chain problems caused by the COVID-19 outbreak, which could delay production of new models from Samsung Electronics. The country's heavy reliance on China for materials and equipment makes it vulnerable to outbreaks.

Huawei, for its part, has been officially promoting its mobile services (HMS) and APP store Appgallery to overseas markets. As HMS's overseas ecosystem is just getting started, many content and functions need to be improved. Strategy Analytics expects overseas sales of Huawei's smartphones to fall by more than 50 per cent in 2020 from a year earlier, with a steeper decline in Western Europe.

On February 13, xiaomi launched its 5G flagship Xiaomi 10 series of mobile phones, the first shot at the 2020 mobile phone launch event. Zhou Yating, an analyst at huajing securities, said Xiaomi's smartphone business is struggling to maintain a gross margin of 8% to 9% because of potential delays in China's 5G base station construction process, which could affect the use of 5G smartphones, that puts pressure on the average selling price of Xiaomi's smartphone business, as well as additional operating costs that could be incurred during the outbreak.

70 per cent of the world's smartphones are produced in China, and the isolation restrictions will affect the global supply chain and manufacturing capacity for smartphones as factories are delayed and labour is in short supply, Strategy Analytics said in its report. In the first half of 2020, Huawei, OPPO, Vivo and Xiaomi will face the risk of a drop in demand at home, while overseas expansion will also be affected by capacity and travel bans. In addition, international brands, including apple, will also be affected by the lack of production capacity, facing the risk of falling demand in the Chinese market.
